If you have more than two radio buttons coming from an array, you can still use the same technique to change the position of a div based on the selected radio button. Here's how you can modify the previous example to work with an array:

In your component, define an array of radio buttons and a variable to keep track of the selected option:

```
radioButtons = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Option 1' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Option 2' },
  { id: 3, name: 'Option 3' },
  // Add additional radio buttons as needed
];

selectedOption: number;
```

In your template, use ngFor to loop over the radio buttons and create the radio button inputs:

```
<div *ngFor="let radioButton of radioButtons">
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="options" [value]="radioButton.id" [(ngModel)]="selectedOption">
    {{ radioButton.name }}
  </label>
</div>

<div [ngClass]="getPositionClass(selectedOption)">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
```

In this example, we are using ngFor to loop over the radioButtons array and create a radio button input for each item. We use [value] to bind the id of the radio button to the input value.

We use the getPositionClass function to return the appropriate CSS class based on the selectedOption value:

```
getPositionClass(optionId: number) {
  for (let i = 0; i < this.radioButtons.length; i++) {
    if (this.radioButtons[i].id === optionId) {
      const positionClass = (i === 0) ? 'top' : (i === this.radioButtons.length - 1) ? 'bottom' : '';
      return { [positionClass]: true };
    }
  }
  return {};
}
```

In this function, we loop over the radioButtons array to find the index of the selected radio button. We then use a ternary operator to return the 'top' class if the selected radio button is the first one, 'bottom' class if it is the last one, or an empty object if it is in between.

In your CSS file, you can define the 'top' and 'bottom' classes to position the div as you desire, as in the previous examples.

This will position the div at the top or bottom of the container, depending on the selected radio button. You can adjust the CSS classes and properties as needed to achieve the desired positioning.

Sure, here's an example CSS for the 'top' and 'bottom' classes:

```
.top {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
}

.bottom {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
}
```

This CSS will position the div at the top or bottom of the container, and stretch it across the entire width of the container. You can modify the properties as needed to achieve the desired look and feel.

To position the div directly under the selected radio button, you can use a combination of CSS and JavaScript to calculate the position of the radio button and set the position of the div accordingly. Here's how you can do it:

In your component, define a variable to keep track of the selected option:

```
selectedOption: number;
```

In your template, use ngFor to loop over the radio buttons and create the radio button inputs (as in the previous example):

```
<div *ngFor="let radioButton of radioButtons">
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="options" [value]="radioButton.id" [(ngModel)]="selectedOption">
    {{ radioButton.name }}
  </label>
</div>

<div #targetDiv class="target-div" [ngStyle]="getPositionStyle()">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
```

In this example, we're adding a 'target-div' class to the div that we want to position below the selected radio button. We're also using the ngStyle directive to dynamically set the style of the div based on the selected radio button.

We're also using a template reference variable (#targetDiv) to reference the div in our JavaScript code.

In your CSS file, define the 'target-div' class:

```
.target-div {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 200px; /* Change this to match the width of your content */
  background-color: white;
  border: 1px solid black;
  padding: 10px;
  display: none;
}
```

We're setting the display property to 'none' for now, because we want to show and hide the div dynamically in our JavaScript code.

In your component, define a method to calculate the position of the selected radio button and set the position of the div:

```
getPositionStyle() {
  const radioButton = document.querySelector(`input[name='options'][value='${this.selectedOption}']`);
  const radioButtonRect = radioButton.getBoundingClientRect();
  const divWidth = 200; // Change this to match the width of your content
  const divLeft = radioButtonRect.left + (radioButtonRect.width / 2) - (divWidth / 2);
  const divTop = radioButtonRect.top + radioButtonRect.height + 5; // Change this margin to match your layout
  return { left: `${divLeft}px`, top: `${divTop}px`, display: this.selectedOption ? 'block' : 'none' };
}
```

In this method, we're using the document.querySelector method to find the selected radio button using its name and value. We're then using the getBoundingClientRect method to get the position of the radio button.

We're calculating the position of the div by subtracting half of its width from the center of the radio button position. We're also adding a margin of 5 pixels (or any other value you choose) to position the div below the radio button.

Finally, we're returning an object with the left, top, and display properties, which we use to dynamically set the style of the div using ngStyle.

The display property is set to 'block' if a radio button is selected, and 'none' if no radio button is selected, so that the div is hidden when no radio button is selected.

That's it! Now the div should be positioned directly under the selected radio button. You can modify the CSS and JavaScript as needed to achieve the desired look and feel.

